00:00:43.468 --> 00:00:45.111
I work for a
shipbuilding company.

00:00:45.698 --> 00:00:49.405
We construct patrol boats, cruise
yachts and high-speed passenger

00:00:49.436 --> 00:00:51.867
and vehicle passenger ferries that
are sold throughout the world.

00:00:53.578 --> 00:00:55.954
I've worked here for seven
years as a welder and

00:00:55.965 --> 00:00:58.051
have spent the last year
as a welding planner.

00:00:59.645 --> 00:01:02.175
We have around 60 welders
working here on each boat.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:06.450
They are coded as A class or B
class, depending on their abilities

00:01:06.476 --> 00:01:09.322
and I have to ensure the right
person is working in the right area.

00:01:16.771 --> 00:01:20.200
Most of our welders come from TAFE and
complete their apprenticeships here.

00:01:21.003 --> 00:01:24.621
But we recruit welders from
time to time as well as develop

00:01:24.644 --> 00:01:26.783
the abilities of our
semi-skilled trade assistants.

00:01:28.069 --> 00:01:30.513
As you're aware, we're
looking for a B class

00:01:30.539 --> 00:01:33.940
welder that's quite
proficient in aluminium. Yep.

00:01:34.127 --> 00:01:37.991
We'll get you down to the training bay ... do
a couple of runs just to see where you're at.

00:01:39.414 --> 00:01:41.898
Every new worker is
assessed upon arrival.

00:01:42.742 --> 00:01:46.071
 If they pass training, they
start at B class doing basic

00:01:46.085 --> 00:01:48.785
jobs until they learn the
skills to move up to A class.

00:01:49.431 --> 00:01:52.045
It looks like you've actually
welded a bit of aluminium before.

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:52.956
Yeah, I've done a little bit.

00:01:53.230 --> 00:01:56.057
What we'll do is look at
getting you in on Monday for

00:01:56.067 --> 00:01:58.555
maybe half a day just to carry
on with a bit of training

00:01:58.618 --> 00:02:01.028
get you up to speed and then we'll
look at you getting on a boat.

00:02:04.443 --> 00:02:10.898
Welders have to consider the size of the material,
its thickness, the weather, gas settings

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:15.095
and heat settings in producing a weld that
is strong and aesthetically presentable.

00:02:18.257 --> 00:02:21.645
I worked as a panel beater for six years
before deciding to move into shipping.

00:02:21.998 --> 00:02:24.668
Some of my skills are
transferable but welding steel

00:02:24.686 --> 00:02:26.764
cars is different to
welding aluminium ships.

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:29.376
This is faster and
has to be neater.

00:02:29.398 --> 00:02:32.440
Luckily  I  have a steady hand and got
the hang of it quickly.

00:02:39.188 --> 00:02:41.617
Drinking water and
keeping fit is crucial.

00:02:42.687 --> 00:02:46.323
The warehouse can get really hot
in summer and cold in winter.

00:02:52.962 --> 00:02:56.220
The welds are randomly x-rayed
by an outside company to

00:02:56.224 --> 00:02:58.824
make sure our work complies
with international standards.

00:02:59.399 --> 00:03:02.737
An 80-metre ship carrying seven
hundred people at 40 knots in

00:03:02.755 --> 00:03:05.964
two-metre seas undergoes a fair
amount of structural stress.

00:03:06.854 --> 00:03:08.287
Okay, guys, well done.

00:03:08.678 --> 00:03:12.379
All those x-rays passed. Done it on
schedule as well, so congratulations.

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:14.028
Cool. Thank you.
Thank you.

